		<td><b>NES controller question</b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />I was looking the NES circuitry and after checking each IC quickly I couldn't figure out which one is the one responsible of the controllers. can anyone answer me please how the NES does this?

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


	<hr width="85%" />

	<table width="85%" cellspacing="3" cellpadding="0" border="0" align="center">
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Author:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b>tepples</b> [ Mon Aug 03, 2009 10:32 am ]</td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td width="10%" nowrap="nowrap">Post subject:&nbsp;</td>
		<td><b></b></td>
	</tr>
	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The controller ports are P4 and P5 on <a href="http://nesdev.com/Ntd_8bit.jpg" class="postlink">this schematic of the Famicom</a>. The ICs that handle this are U7 and U8, which appear to be 6-pin 40H368 (like 74368?) bus drivers. The CPU puts out three relevant signals: last value written to $4016 D0 (strobe), $4016 /OE (player 1 clock), and $4017 /OE (player 2 clock), which gets sent to the controllers. Then the 368s put signals from the controllers on D0, D3, and D4.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


